"""
slopbox — run an untrusted process in an unprivileged bwrap slopbox.

    slopbox                 start the UI (network approval + change review)
    slopbox CMD [ARGS...]   run CMD slopboxed

Network model: the slopbox has NO real network — only loopback. A tiny
forwarder inside the slopbox listens on 127.0.0.1:8080 (the proxy the program
is told to use) and hands each accepted connection's FD out to the UI over a
Unix socket (SCM_RIGHTS). The UI feeds that socket to an in-process mitmproxy,
which gates it against the rules / asks you, and performs the real upstream
fetch in the UI's own network context. No slirp, no host ports reachable from
the slopbox, no proxy listening anywhere the slopbox could abuse. If no UI is
running, the forwarder has nowhere to hand connections, so the slopbox simply
has no network — it never blocks waiting on an absent human.

Filesystem model: the UI owns ONE pyfuse3 overlay mount, served from a
dedicated trio thread and created the ordinary way (`pyfuse3.init` via the
setuid `fusermount3` helper — no root, no user namespace, no fd-passing, no
mount(2)/pivot_root anywhere). That single mount is *multiplexed*: its synthetic
root lists one subfolder per live slopbox, `<mnt>/<box_id>`, each presenting a
copy-on-write overlay of lower=`/` plus that box's private upper. A box's
identity is its stable integer box_id, minted at creation and never changed.
Files are content-addressed pool blobs; dirs and symlinks are sqlar rows served
from the in-RAM Index mirror. `up/` holds NO file/dir/symlink artifacts — it is
only the discovery sentinel (an empty dir). A slopbox writing to
`<mnt>/<box_id>/etc/hostname` reads through to the host file unless it wrote there.

Because the UI serves every filesystem op, it sits in the I/O path exactly like
it already does for network requests: the Changes view updates live as writes
happen, and a per-write policy hook (policy_check) is the obvious place where a
deny/prompt would attach. Provenance (pid/exe/argv of the writer) is captured
synchronously and recorded in the per-box `<box_id>.sqlar`. Since the UI is now
the mount provider, `slopbox CMD` REQUIRES a running UI and fails fast otherwise.

Security note: policy_check is a v1 always-allow stub — the per-write enforcement
seam exists but is not yet enforcing. The system is "security-ready, not
security-complete": writes are captured and attributed but never blocked at the
FUSE layer in this version.

Isolation: the runner does `bwrap --bind <mnt>/<box_id> / …` with own
PID/IPC/UTS/net namespaces, runs as you, and drops all caps EXCEPT CAP_SYS_ADMIN
and CAP_NET_ADMIN — a box keeps those two so it can itself host a nested box
(unshare pid/ipc/uts/mount + bring up loopback in the nested netns); a provably-
leaf box (run_on_untrusted) drops ALL. Those two caps come from one of two paths,
chosen automatically per run: (1) AMBIENT — the process already holds them (fast
path, e.g. running as root or with the caps granted by the host); (2) USERNS — if
ambient caps are absent, the runner adds `--unshare-user` to create a fresh
UNPRIVILEGED user namespace and synthesizes the two caps inside it, which lets
slopbox run with no ambient privilege under rootless Podman / Fedora toolbox
(where nested user namespaces are allowed). The userns path keeps the launching
uid via bwrap's default identity map (no --uid/--gid), and retains the same two
caps for now (a later change will drop them entirely there). If neither path is
available the runner refuses with an actionable error. Because CAP_SYS_ADMIN is near root-
equivalent for many escapes, a slopbox is an INSPECTION/REVIEW sandbox, not a
hard containment boundary against a hostile payload — compose it inside a
stronger sandbox if you need real containment. The bind-as-root confines the box
to its own subfolder; it cannot reach `<mnt>/` or another box's subtree. Same uid
as the UI, so no allow_other.

Options (slopbox [FLAGS] -- CMD ...; the command MUST follow `--`):
  -n         enable networking via mitmproxy (default: off)
  -t         enable process tracing (default: off)
  -d         direct host access / no capture (default: off)
  -w HOST    pre-allow HOST for this session (repeatable)
  -C DIR     working directory inside the slopbox (default: cwd)

A box is identified by its stable integer box_id. Its human-readable name (and
optional parent_box_id for nesting) are stored in the box's `<box_id>.sqlar`
meta table. Renaming a box is a meta-only label write — the id and backing dirs
never change.
"""

